    "fb-daily-20260430-01-la-nueva-ley-del-ruido-entra-en-vigor-y-cambia-las-reglas-para-construir-viviend": {
        title: "The new noise law comes into force and changes the rules for building housing in Switzerland",
        description: "The partial revision of the Federal Law on Environmental Protection (LPE) and the Noise Protection Ordinance (OP) has been in force since April 1, 2026.",
        keywords: "new, noise, enter, force, change, rules, build, housing",
        keywordsLocalized: true,
        category: "Housing",
        hub: "vivienda",
        slug: "actualidad-2026-04-30-1-la-nueva-ley-del-ruido-entra-en-vigor-y-cambia-las-reglas-para-construir-viviend",
        readingTime: 2,
        dateUpdated: "April 30, 2026",
        featuredImage: "media/guides/actualidad-ley-ruido-vivienda-suiza.jpg",
        imageAlt: "New noise law for housing construction in Switzerland",
        summary: "Since April 1, 2026, the partial revision of the Federal Law on Environmental Protection (LPE) and the Ordinance on Environmental Protection has been in force.",
        relatedSlugs: [],
        content: `<div class="article-content"> 
<p>As of April 1, 2026, the partial revision of the Federal Law on Environmental Protection (LPE) and the Noise Protection Ordinance (OPB) has been in force. In practice, cantonal and communal authorities can now authorize the construction of housing in noisy areas even if the immission limit values ​​are slightly exceeded in front of the windows. Until now, these limits blocked thousands of projects near roads, train tracks or tram lines, especially in Geneva, Vaud and Zurich, where the lack of apartments has been the favorite topic of any conversation between neighbors for years.</p> 
<p>The new rule is not a blank check. When the limit values ​​cannot be respected with reasonable efforts, the building permit is only granted if appropriate compensatory measures are installed in the rooms, such as controlled ventilation to avoid having to open the window, or specific protections on the facades. The stated idea of the Federal Council is to better coordinate the fight against noise with urban development towards the interior, which is the official line since the revision of the LAT.</p> 
<p>For those looking for an apartment, this changes little in the short term, but it is worth knowing that a perfectly legal new building can be in an area where permission would not have even been given before. If the ad says "lumineux et calme" but the property faces a busy road, mechanical ventilation and reinforced glass are now the norm, not a luxury. Before signing, it is worth asking the owner for the project's acoustic report, opening the window during rush hour and asking what ventilation system the home is equipped with.</p> 
<p>For those considering buying or investing in a new project, the reform opens the door to more offerings in well-connected neighborhoods that until now were frozen. The Confederation speaks of some tens of thousands of potential homes throughout Switzerland. The measure will take time to be noticed in the market, because between planning, oppositions and construction, in this country no one builds a building in six months, except in electoral speeches.</p> 
</div>`
    },

    "fb-daily-20260430-02-defectos-de-construccion-ahora-tienes-60-dias-para-reclamar-y-eso-cambia-muchas-": {
        title: "Construction defects: you now have 60 days to claim and that changes many things",
        description: "Since January 1, 2026, the review of the warranty right for defects in the Code of Obligations is in force. The main novelty is a single legal period of 60 days for…",
        keywords: "defects, construction, now, you have, days, claim, change, many",
        keywordsLocalized: true,
        category: "Housing",
        hub: "vivienda",
        slug: "actualidad-2026-04-30-2-defectos-de-construccion-ahora-tienes-60-dias-para-reclamar-y-eso-cambia-muchas-",
        readingTime: 2,
        dateUpdated: "April 30, 2026",
        featuredImage: "media/guides/actualidad-defectos-construccion-suiza.jpg",
        imageAlt: "60-day deadline to claim construction defects in Switzerland",
        summary: "Since January 1, 2026, the review of the warranty right for defects in the Code of Obligations is in force. The main novelty is a legal deadline…",
        relatedSlugs: [],
        content: `<div class="article-content"> 
<p>From January 1, 2026, the review of the warranty right for defects in the Code of Obligations is in force. The main novelty is a single legal period of 60 days to notify the builder or seller of any defect, whether visible upon receipt of the work or discovered later. Previously, the law required notification of the defect "immediately", an elastic expression that in practice was usually interpreted as three to ten days, with the tenant or buyer eternally exposed to losing their rights for a minor delay.</p> 
<p>The change is important because the deadline is now imperative. Any clause in a contract signed on or after January 1, 2026 that reduces those 60 days to the detriment of the buyer or owner is void. The same applies to the five-year statute of limitations in real estate construction, which cannot be shortened contractually either. And people who buy a new home or a building less than two years old from delivery now have a legal right to free repair, with conditions that the seller can no longer avoid with a standard clause.</p> 
<p>For Spaniards who buy an apartment here, this is good news. Many Swiss contracts came with clauses that limited the seller's liability to such an extent that claiming a serious defect was almost a legal miracle. These clauses remain legal for the rest of the guarantee regime, but no longer for the points protected by the new law. If you signed a contract before 2026, the previous regime still applies, so it is worth checking the exact date before fighting with the promoter.</p> 
<p>In practical terms, it is advisable to document everything that is seen from the handover of the keys: photos, videos, a technical visit with an expert if the operation is important. And put any claim in writing, ideally by certified letter, so that the 60 days do not become a matter of word against word. Switzerland doesn't forgive deadlines, but at least now you know what it is.</p> 
</div>`
    },

